abstract: Here’s a look at what each of the candidates for the Democratic nomination has said about impeaching President Trump.
snippet: Here’s a look at what each of the candidates for the Democratic nomination has said about impeaching President Trump.
lead_paragraph: [Update, May 29: After Robert S. Mueller III’s public remarks, more Democratic presidential candidates called for impeachment proceedings.]

abstract: Senator Elizabeth Warren said she would not participate in a Fox News town hall-style event, but some of her 2020 Democratic rivals have taken up the network’s offer.
snippet: Senator Elizabeth Warren said she would not participate in a Fox News town hall-style event, but some of her 2020 Democratic rivals have taken up the network’s offer.
lead_paragraph: Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts on Tuesday broke from her Democratic rivals by declining to participate in a Fox News town hall, denouncing the cable news channel as “a hate-for-profit racket” that seeks to turns Americans against one another.

abstract: The nation’s first presidential caucus is always important, but with more than 20 Democrats running this time, the need for a strong showing is far more urgent.
snippet: The nation’s first presidential caucus is always important, but with more than 20 Democrats running this time, the need for a strong showing is far more urgent.
lead_paragraph: IOWA CITY — It may be nearly nine months until the first balloting of the 2020 primary, but candidates are already practically tripping over one another in Iowa.

headline_main: Iowa’s Likely Outcome for 2020 Contenders: A Field of Broken Dreams
headline_print_headline: 2020 Contenders Confront Iowa’s Field of Broken Dreams

abstract: Ms. Warren has hired about 50 people in Iowa, giving her a head start at organizing for next year’s caucuses. But it’s a strategy loaded with risk.

lead_paragraph: WEST DES MOINES, Iowa — It was game time at the “Persist Party.”

abstract: The New York Times sent a climate policy survey to the 18 declared candidates. They all want to stick to the Paris Agreement. Beyond that, they diverge.
snippet: The New York Times sent a climate policy survey to the 18 declared candidates. They all want to stick to the Paris Agreement. Beyond that, they diverge.
lead_paragraph: For Democrats vying to unseat President Trump, acknowledging climate change is easy. Deciding what to do about it is the hard part.

headline_main: The Complexities of the Black Vote

abstract: Senator Elizabeth Warren has spent millions to build her campaign staff, while Mayor Pete Buttigieg spent less than 10 percent of what he raised in the first quarter.
snippet: Senator Elizabeth Warren has spent millions to build her campaign staff, while Mayor Pete Buttigieg spent less than 10 percent of what he raised in the first quarter.
lead_paragraph: Some Democratic candidates for president are already spending furiously to saturate Facebook with ads as they race to qualify for the first debates this summer. Others are carefully husbanding their resources, banking cash in hopes of unloading it in a burst as the primaries near.
